In chapters xi, xxiii, xxiv we find a statement of that which was called by later theologians the ‘hypo- static union.’ It receives a simple expression in the words of ch. xv, ‘homo est enim cum deo iunctus, et deus cum homine copulatus⁵.' Tertullian had sought to state it in philosophical terms of a sort: ‘uidemus duplicem statum, non confusum, secl coniunctum in una persona, deum et hominem Iesum⁶’; and again, ‘cum dnae substantiae censeantur in Christo Iesu⁷.⁷ We have already alluded to a certain resemblance in Novatian’s teaching to that which was afterwards known as Nes- torianism.
